# Claude Code Project Rules

## Code Style and Formatting

### Character Usage
- NEVER use emojis in any files (code, documentation, comments, commit messages)
- NEVER use em-dashes (-) or en-dashes (-)
- Use regular hyphens (-) for all dash purposes
- Use standard ASCII characters only in code and comments
- UTF-8 is acceptable for user-facing strings, but avoid decorative Unicode

### Documentation Style
- Use plain Markdown without emoji decorations
- Use regular hyphens for bullet points and lists
- Use asterisks (*) or underscores (_) for emphasis, not emoji
- Keep all documentation readable in plain text terminals

### Comments
- Write clear, technical comments without emoji
- Use standard punctuation only
- Focus on explaining WHY, not WHAT (code shows what)
- For complex logic, add detailed multi-line comments
- Simple, obvious operations need no comment

### Commit Messages
- Follow conventional commits format: `type(scope): description`
- No emoji in commit messages
- Types: feat, fix, docs, style, refactor, test, chore
- Keep first line under 72 characters
- Use imperative mood: "add feature" not "added feature"
- Body lines wrapped at 72 characters

## Language Preferences

### Programming Languages
- Primary: BASH, Python, Go
- Always include comments for code clarity
- Detailed comments only for complex logic
- Simple operations can have brief or no comments

### Cross-Platform Compatibility
- All applications must be fully cross-platform compatible
- Target platforms: Linux, macOS, Windows
- Use path separators correctly (os.path.join in Python, filepath in Go)
- Handle line endings appropriately
- Never hardcode platform-specific paths

## File Naming Conventions

### General Rules
- Use underscores (_) instead of spaces in ALL filenames
- Use lowercase for most filenames
- Follow Linux-friendly conventions
- Examples:
  - Good: my_script.sh, config_parser.py, user_data.json
  - Bad: My Script.sh, config-parser.py, "user data.json"

### Configuration and Data Storage
- CLI flags for database connections and runtime overrides
- User data and settings stored under: ~/.app_name/ (where app_name matches the application name)
- NEVER use ~/.config/app_name/ or any other path variant - always ~/.app_name/
- Store configuration in standard formats in this preference order: YAML, JSON, TOML

## License Headers

### Required on All New Source Files
- Every new source file must include the appropriate license header for the project
- Check the project LICENSE file to determine the correct header format
- For dual AGPLv3/Commercial projects, use the AGPLv3 SPDX header:
  - `// SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later` (Go/BASH)
  - `# SPDX-License-Identifier: AGPL-3.0-or-later` (Python/BASH)
- Never omit the license header from a new file
- Never change an existing license header without explicit instruction

## Project Structure

### Required Files
- README.md with clear project description and usage
- CHANGELOG.md following Keep a Changelog format (update with EVERY change)
- PLANNING.md tracking goals, milestones, open questions, and decisions
- CLAUDE.md documenting project context, build steps, and conventions for AI sessions
- ARCHITECTURE.md documenting components, data flow, and key design decisions
- LICENSE file
- .gitignore appropriate for languages used
- CONTRIBUTING.md if project accepts contributions

### Documentation
- Keep documentation up to date with code changes
- Document all public APIs and exported functions
- Include usage examples in README.md
- Keep installation instructions current
- Update ARCHITECTURE.md when structural changes are made
- Update PLANNING.md when goals or decisions change

## Git and Branch Workflow

### Branch Rules
- NEVER commit directly to master
- NEVER push directly to master
- All changes must go through a feature branch and pull request
- Branch naming: type/short-description (e.g. feat/add-login, fix/null-pointer)
- One logical change per branch

### Pull Requests
- PRs must target master
- All tests must pass before a PR is suggested
- CHANGELOG.md must be updated in the same branch as the change
- PR description must summarize what changed and why

### Commits
- Atomic commits - one logical change per commit
- Never combine unrelated changes in a single commit
- Never amend or force-push commits that have been shared

## Development Workflow

### Before Making Changes
1. Read CLAUDE.md and ARCHITECTURE.md to understand the project
2. Review existing code style in the project
3. Check CHANGELOG.md format and version state
4. Confirm the approach with the user before starting

### Scope Control
- Only modify files directly relevant to the task at hand
- Related files (e.g. tests for code changed) may be updated when clearly necessary
- NEVER refactor, reformat, or restructure code that was not part of the request
- NEVER rename variables, functions, or files opportunistically
- If improvements outside scope are noticed, mention them - do not make them unilaterally

### When Making Changes
1. Update CHANGELOG.md in the same commit as code changes
2. Add/update tests if applicable
3. Update documentation if behavior changes
4. Ensure cross-platform compatibility
5. Add license header to any new source files

### Destructive Operations
- ALWAYS confirm with the user before deleting any file
- ALWAYS confirm before overwriting a file that was not explicitly part of the task
- NEVER delete directories without explicit instruction
- When in doubt, ask - do not assume deletion is intended

### Dependencies
- NEVER introduce a new dependency without discussing it with the user first
- Prefer standard library solutions over third-party packages when reasonable
- If a dependency is needed, explain why and wait for approval before adding it
- Document new dependencies in the appropriate file (go.mod, requirements.txt, etc.)

### Testing
- Run all existing tests before suggesting a commit or PR
- Tests must pass - do not suggest a PR with failing tests
- If tests cannot be run, say so explicitly and explain why
- Verify cross-platform compatibility where applicable
- Check for breaking changes in public APIs

## Methodical Approach

### Step-by-Step Development
- Discuss and agree on next steps before implementing
- Break complex tasks into smaller, manageable pieces
- Validate each step before proceeding
- Be precise when requirements call for it
- Move quickly when appropriate (prototyping, exploration)

### Decision Points
- Always confirm the approach before major changes
- Ask for clarification when requirements are ambiguous
- Propose solutions with trade-offs explained
- Default to standards and best practices unless told otherwise
- When multiple valid approaches exist, present options rather than picking unilaterally

## Application Types

### CLI Applications
- Use argparse (Python) or flag/cobra (Go) for argument parsing
- Provide --help output with clear usage examples
- Support --version flag
- Exit with appropriate status codes (0 success, non-zero failure)
- Use stderr for errors, stdout for data output
- Support --verbose / --quiet flags for log verbosity

### GUI Applications
- Must work cross-platform (Linux, macOS, Windows)
- Use appropriate toolkit (GTK, Qt, or web-based)
- Follow platform UI guidelines where possible
- Provide keyboard shortcuts for common actions
- Never hardcode font sizes, colors, or paths

### Services and Daemons
- Handle SIGTERM and SIGINT for graceful shutdown
- Handle SIGHUP for configuration reload where appropriate
- Write PID file to standard location when daemonizing
- Provide a systemd unit file (and launchd plist / Windows service wrapper for cross-platform)
- Log to stderr by default; support configurable log destination
- Never block the main loop on non-critical work
- Document all runtime flags and environment variables

## Error Handling

### General Principles
- Always handle errors explicitly - no ignored return values
- Provide clear, actionable error messages that describe what failed and why
- Log errors at the appropriate level
- Exit gracefully on fatal errors with a non-zero status code
- No silent failures under any circumstances

### Logging
- Use standard logging libraries for the language
- Include timestamps in all log output
- Use appropriate log levels: DEBUG, INFO, WARNING, ERROR, CRITICAL
- Make log verbosity configurable via flag or environment variable
- Do not log sensitive data (credentials, tokens, PII)

## Security Considerations

- NEVER commit credentials, tokens, API keys, or secrets of any kind
- Use environment variables or files under ~/.app_name/ for sensitive data
- Validate and sanitize all user input
- Use prepared statements for all database queries
- Follow principle of least privilege for file permissions and process capabilities
- Do not store sensitive data in plain text without explicit instruction

## Configuration and Secrets (Web Override)

- Web applications are configured exclusively via environment variables
- The ~/.app_name/ home directory convention does NOT apply to web applications
- Local config lives in .env (never committed - always in .gitignore)
- .env.example is committed with all keys present and safe placeholder values
- Never hardcode any secret, key, token, or credential in source files
- Never read os.Environ / os.Getenv outside the dedicated config package
- Production secrets are managed by the deployment environment - never in the repo
- If a new environment variable is added, it must also be added to .env.example
  with a descriptive placeholder value and a comment explaining it

## Database and Migrations

- All schema changes must be expressed as migration files in migrations/
- Migration files are numbered sequentially and never edited after being applied
  to any environment - create a new migration instead
- Never write raw SQL strings outside the repository layer
- All queries must use parameterized statements - no string interpolation or
  string concatenation to build queries
- The repository layer is the only place that imports the database package
- Service layer must not construct or execute queries directly

## Security (Web Additions)

- Validate and sanitize all user input before use - never trust request data
- CSRF protection must be in place for any state-changing endpoint
- CORS must be explicitly configured - never use wildcard (*) in production
- Security headers (Content-Security-Policy, X-Frame-Options, etc.) must be set
  via middleware - never set them per-handler
- Rate limiting must be applied to all authentication and password reset endpoints
- Never expose raw database errors, stack traces, or internal paths to clients
- Never log full request bodies if they may contain passwords, tokens, or PII
- Passwords must be hashed with bcrypt, argon2, or equivalent - never stored plain
  or with weak hashing (MD5, SHA1)

## HTTP and API Conventions

- Handlers must be thin: parse request, call service, serialize response
- No business logic in handlers - it belongs in the service layer
- No database access in handlers - it belongs in the repository layer
- All API errors return structured JSON with error, code, and request_id fields
- Use appropriate HTTP status codes (see ARCHITECTURE.md for the convention table)
- All responses within a request context must include the X-Request-ID header
- Never return a 200 with an error body - use the correct 4xx or 5xx status

## Frontend Conventions

- All API calls must be centralized in the api/ module - never fetch from components
- Never store secrets, tokens, or sensitive data in localStorage or sessionStorage
  unless there is no alternative and the risk is explicitly documented
- HttpOnly cookies are preferred over localStorage for auth tokens
- Never inline sensitive values in HTML or JavaScript source

## File Naming (Web Additions)

- Backend files: underscores (consistent with base .clauderules)
- Frontend files: follow the existing convention in the project (hyphens are
  acceptable for component filenames if that is what the project already uses)
- Migration files: NNN_snake_case_description.sql (e.g. 001_create_users.sql)
- Never mix conventions within the same layer

## Testing (Web Additions)

- Service layer tests must use mocked repositories - no real database calls
- Handler tests must use an HTTP test client - no real network calls
- Integration tests that require a database must use a separate test database,
  never the development or production database
- End-to-end tests cover critical user flows only - not exhaustive UI coverage
- Never hardcode test credentials or secrets - use environment variables or
  test-specific fixture helpers

## What Claude Must Not Do in Web Projects

- Must not run database migrations automatically without explicit instruction
- Must not modify .env - suggest changes to .env.example only
- Must not add a new dependency (npm or backend) without discussion
- Must not bypass the repository layer to query the database directly
- Must not add inline styles or hardcoded colors to frontend code
- Must not expose a new endpoint without considering auth and rate limiting
- Must not change CORS or CSP configuration without explicit instruction
